node.title: NSW's ninth Omicron COVID case is a student who hasn't travelled overseas
node.alt: A child in a car receives a COVID nasal swab
node.description: NSW Health confirms one further case of the Omicron COVID-19 variant of concern in a school student who has noÂ overseas travel history.
node.content:
["NSW Health is concerned the state's ninth Omicron COVID-19 infection \"may have been acquired in the community\".", "The latest case, a student at Regents Park Christian School in Western Sydney, has not been overseas and has no links to people who have travelled abroad.", "Health Minister Brad Hazzard said two other students at the school had\u00a0\"early indications\" of Omicron infection and were undergoing further testing.", "\"I'm expecting those results should be back later today,\" he said.", "Mr Hazzard said this latest case was concerning as it appears to have been transmitted on NSW soil.", "\"It is a challenge,\" he said.", "The Omicron infection numbers are slowly growing in NSW and last night authorities confirmed the state's eighth case was a passenger on a flight from Singapore to Sydney on November 28.", "Every person on the affected Singapore Airlines flight has been asked to get tested immediately and isolate until they receive a negative result.", "Two passengers from this flight have already previously tested positive to the Omicron variant but neither spent time in the community due to new quarantine rules introduced in NSW.", "Positive Omicron cases have also been identified in passengers on\u00a0two other Qatar Airways flights from Doha, which landed on November 25 and 27 respectively.", "Research is still being done on the new variant, which was first identified in southern Africa, but yesterday\u00a0Chief Medical Officer Paul Kelly said there was \"no real evidence\" that it was more severe than the Delta variant.", "\"So we remain, I remain\u00a0cautiously optimistic, but we need\u00a0further information,\" he said.", "NSW recorded 337 new COVID-19 cases and no deaths in the 24 hours to 8pm yesterday.", "Currently\u00a094.6 per cent of people aged 16 and over have received a first dose of a COVID-19 vaccine, and 92.6 per cent are fully vaccinated.", "Of the people aged 12 to 15, 81.3 per cent have received a first dose of COVID-19 vaccine, and 76.9 per cent are fully vaccinated.", "More to come.", "", "
Heavily mutated Omicron variant puts scientist on alert
"]
